Lets do some feature engineering - the data set we start with is the “raw material” - We can use those to make more meaning, aid interpretation

house <- housing_prices %>% 
  mutate(bedrooms_per_house = total_bedrooms / households, 
         rooms_per_house = total_rooms / households,
         people_per_house = population / households,
         bedrooms_per_person = total_bedrooms / population, 
         rooms_per_person = total_rooms / population,
         bedrooms_per_room = total_bedrooms / total_rooms,
         non_bedrooms_per_house = room_per_house - bedrooms_per_house)

library(raster)
library(leaflet)

raster <- rasterFromXYZ(housing_prices %>% 
  dplyr::select(longitude, latitude, median_house_value), crs = "+proj=longlat +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84 +no_defs")

pal <- colorNumeric(c("blue", "red", "yellow"), values(raster),
  na.color = "transparent")

leaflet() %>% 
  addTiles() %>% 
  addRasterImage(raster, colors = pal, opacity = 0.7) %>% 
  addLegend(pal = pal, values = values(raster),
    title = "Median House Value")

# regress median_house_value ~ median_income

lm1 <- lm(median_house_value ~ median_income, data = housing_prices)

summary(lm1)

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(lm1)

  • residuals vs fitted - flat line indicates that there is a good random scattering therefore residuals are independent
  • normal q-q - line shows a fairly straight line indicating a normal distribution
  • scale-location - residuals appear fairly randomly spread which satisfies the assumption of homoskedasticity
  • residuals vs leverage - cant see any cook’s distance lines therefore the outlier cases are not influential

results suggest a 1 unit increase in median_income is associated with a 42420 increase in median_house_value, holding all other factors constant.

a 1 unit increase in housing_median_age is associated with a 1568 increase in median_house_age, holding all other factors constant.

task 1 ##########

lm3


Call:
lm(formula = median_house_value ~ log(median_income) + housing_median_age + 
    population + log(median_income):housing_median_age, data = housing_prices)

Coefficients:
                          (Intercept)                     log(median_income)                     housing_median_age  
                           -12674.297                             130280.757                                989.159  
                           population  log(median_income):housing_median_age  
                                2.988                                455.932

I would say the predicator is justified given that it would be expected that given a person’s age, they are more likely to have a higher income – having a greater impact on the median housing price.

should probably change median_house_value to natural logarithm to counter a non-linear distribution for a more accurate model.
